00:19:58,762 --> 00:20:00,460
I'm gonna take you
for an elegant lunch.

246
00:20:00,590 --> 00:20:02,505
Great.

247
00:20:02,636 --> 00:20:05,508
This is it?
This is how you
come to see me?

248
00:20:05,639 --> 00:20:07,249
Where's your blazer?

249
00:20:09,599 --> 00:20:11,471
<i>Of course they know</i><i>
I have a son.</i>

250
00:20:11,601 --> 00:20:13,603
<i>They just don't know</i><i>
how old you are.</i>

251
00:20:13,734 --> 00:20:15,605
Jay:
How old do they
think I am?

252
00:20:15,736 --> 00:20:17,651
Leona: Jay,
I needed the job,

253
00:20:17,781 --> 00:20:20,697
so I told them
I had a son to support,

254
00:20:20,828 --> 00:20:23,657
one that was young enough
to be in the free-lunch
program at school.

255
00:20:23,787 --> 00:20:26,573
There's no free-lunch
program in college.

256
00:20:26,703 --> 00:20:28,618
There is in grade school.

257
00:20:28,749 --> 00:20:30,620
Oh, mother!

258
00:20:30,751 --> 00:20:32,579
How old do they
think you are?

259
00:20:32,709 --> 00:20:34,537
Younger than springtime.

260
00:20:34,668 --> 00:20:36,974
[ Both laughing ]

261
00:20:37,105 --> 00:20:39,673
So what's up?

262
00:20:39,803 --> 00:20:42,371
I'm getting married.

263
00:20:44,721 --> 00:20:47,463
- You can't be.
- Why not?

264
00:20:47,594 --> 00:20:49,378
You're only
eight years old.

265
00:20:49,509 --> 00:20:52,381
- Oh!
- [ Both laugh ]

266
00:20:59,736 --> 00:21:02,565
- Is he in?
- Yes.

267
00:21:02,696 --> 00:21:04,524
Would you ask
if I could see him,
please?

268
00:21:04,654 --> 00:21:06,439
Whom shall I say
is calling?

269
00:21:06,569 --> 00:21:08,919
Rosenthol or Roberts?

270
00:21:11,531 --> 00:21:13,315
Just buzz him, honey.

271
00:21:16,666 --> 00:21:18,189
- <i>[ Intercom buzzes ]</i>
- Yes?

272
00:21:18,320 --> 00:21:21,454
Secretary: <i>Leona Roberts</i><i>
is here to see you,</i><i>
Mr. Nederland.</i>

273
00:21:21,584 --> 00:21:22,542
Yeah, send her in.

274
00:21:29,549 --> 00:21:31,638
Leona.

275
00:21:31,768 --> 00:21:34,554
- Mr. Nederland.
- Sit down.

276
00:21:34,684 --> 00:21:36,643
Thank you.

277
00:21:36,773 --> 00:21:38,819
You're looking
marvelous today.

278
00:21:38,949 --> 00:21:41,604
I tell the others,
"look after yourself
the way Leona does,

279
00:21:41,735 --> 00:21:44,433
- and you'll be
a success here."
- Oh, well, I try.

280
00:21:44,564 --> 00:21:46,522
After all,
sales is image

281
00:21:46,653 --> 00:21:48,132
and you have
the right image.

282
00:21:48,263 --> 00:21:51,614
Well, I'm more than image,
Mr. Nederland.

283
00:21:51,745 --> 00:21:53,312
I've got experience.

284
00:21:53,442 --> 00:21:55,705
I started here a year ago
as a receptionist.

285
00:21:55,836 --> 00:21:57,794
Now I have
my real-estate license,

286
00:21:57,925 --> 00:21:59,666
and I'm one of
the best producers
in this office,

287
00:21:59,796 --> 00:22:00,841
and I did it
all on my own.

288
00:22:00,971 --> 00:22:03,800
I'm well aware
of your record.

289
00:22:03,931 --> 00:22:06,063
Then make me
the sales agent
for the park cinq.

290
00:22:06,194 --> 00:22:09,589
[ Chuckles ]

291
00:22:09,719 --> 00:22:11,373
You are hungry,
aren't you?

292
00:22:11,504 --> 00:22:14,550
Park cinq is
a test case for every
co-op in New York.

293
00:22:14,681 --> 00:22:16,509
If we can sell
the park cinq,

294
00:22:16,639 --> 00:22:18,685
every landlord,
every apartment,

295
00:22:18,815 --> 00:22:20,295
will be lined up
to convert.

296
00:22:20,426 --> 00:22:22,341
And I can sell those
apartments faster

297
00:22:22,471 --> 00:22:24,604
than anybody
in this office
and you know it.

298
00:22:32,786 --> 00:22:34,570
Have you seen these?

299
00:22:34,701 --> 00:22:36,398
Pictures of
my new apartment?

300
00:22:36,529 --> 00:22:37,878
No.

301
00:22:38,008 --> 00:22:41,185
- Oh, the dining room?
- Mm-hmm.

302
00:22:41,316 --> 00:22:42,709
That's very nice.

303
00:22:42,839 --> 00:22:45,102
This is the library.

304
00:22:45,233 --> 00:22:48,802
Mmm.
Very nice.

305
00:22:48,932 --> 00:22:51,370
What do you think
of the bedroom?

306
00:22:56,592 --> 00:22:58,681
I don't see it.

307
00:22:58,812 --> 00:23:01,815
You'll just have
to come up and see
it then, won't you?

308
00:23:01,945 --> 00:23:04,383
It's got mirrors
on the walls and ceiling.

309
00:23:29,756 --> 00:23:31,584
Come on, come on,
come on!

310
00:23:31,714 --> 00:23:33,673
It will take me
just one second.

311
00:23:33,803 --> 00:23:37,416
Thank you.

312
00:23:37,546 --> 00:23:40,636
The bedroom.
I'm sure that's
your main--

313
00:23:40,767 --> 00:23:42,769
I heard about you guys.

314
00:23:42,899 --> 00:23:45,162
Yeah, I heard about
you all the way
back east.

315
00:23:45,293 --> 00:23:47,817
Go on in.
I'll be right in there.
Get my purse, please.

316
00:23:47,948 --> 00:23:50,254
Could you get me
my purse, please?

317
00:23:50,385 --> 00:23:53,649
<i>I'll be right there.</i>

318
00:23:53,780 --> 00:23:56,783
Thank you very much.

319
00:23:56,913 --> 00:23:59,263
Some of you had the privilege
of working under me

320
00:23:59,394 --> 00:24:00,830
at the park cinq,

321
00:24:00,961 --> 00:24:03,224
and you made
a lot of money.

322
00:24:03,354 --> 00:24:05,705
Well...

323
00:24:05,835 --> 00:24:08,751
This building
is a new challenge,

324
00:24:08,882 --> 00:24:11,319
and I expect
each and every
one of you

325
00:24:11,450 --> 00:24:12,886
to meet that challenge,

326
00:24:13,016 --> 00:24:15,715
because your record
reflects on mine.

327
00:24:15,845 --> 00:24:18,326
- <i>[ Door opens ]</i>
- Man: <i>Excuse me!</i>

328
00:24:18,457 --> 00:24:20,676
Excuse me.
Excuse me!

329
00:24:20,807 --> 00:24:22,896
Whoa whoa whoa.
Who are you,

330
00:24:23,026 --> 00:24:24,680
the delivery boy?

331
00:24:24,811 --> 00:24:26,160
Yeah, you're
the warden?

332
00:24:26,290 --> 00:24:27,857
That's right, baby.

333
00:24:27,988 --> 00:24:29,685
And if you're
working for me,

334
00:24:29,816 --> 00:24:31,774
you're late
and may be fired.

335
00:24:31,905 --> 00:24:34,037
Well, first of all,

336
00:24:34,168 --> 00:24:36,431
I'm late because
there was a fire
on the b.M.T.,

337
00:24:36,562 --> 00:24:37,563
and secondly,
you're not gonna
fire me

338
00:24:37,693 --> 00:24:39,303
because I'm gonna
be your best salesman.

339
00:24:39,434 --> 00:24:41,131
Now, where's my desk?

340
00:24:45,788 --> 00:24:48,661
And I guess
that's yours,

341
00:24:48,791 --> 00:24:51,664
so let's see.

342
00:24:55,450 --> 00:24:56,669
That oughta do it.

343
00:24:56,799 --> 00:24:58,801
Do what?

344
00:24:58,932 --> 00:25:00,760
I hear you're very good
at snapping your fingers.

345
00:25:00,890 --> 00:25:02,892
This way, we can't
see each other.

346
00:25:03,023 --> 00:25:05,765
You won't have to snap,
and I won't have
to ignore you.

347
00:25:05,895 --> 00:25:08,158
<i>We're gonna</i><i>
get along just fine.</i>

348
00:25:21,824 --> 00:25:23,652
Your tie is too wide.

349
00:25:23,783 --> 00:25:25,262
And in the right light,

350
00:25:25,393 --> 00:25:28,570
your earrings could
signal the entire
seventh fleet.

351
00:25:35,055 --> 00:25:36,709
Leona Roberts.

352
00:25:36,839 --> 00:25:39,581
Paul summerton.

353
00:25:44,891 --> 00:25:47,197
<i>[ Ballroom music playing ]</i>

354
00:26:05,694 --> 00:26:08,305
- Which one is he?
- He's married, Leona.

355
00:26:08,436 --> 00:26:10,046
I don't care.

356
00:26:10,177 --> 00:26:12,875
Nederland
will be jealous.

357
00:26:14,834 --> 00:26:16,923
[ Chuckles ]

358
00:26:17,053 --> 00:26:20,013
Hmm.

359
00:26:20,143 --> 00:26:22,450
Table number 11.

360
00:26:22,581 --> 00:26:25,540
<i>See the man</i><i>
on the left?</i>

361
00:26:25,671 --> 00:26:28,717
<i>Mustache</i><i>
with glasses.</i><i>
See him?</i>

362
00:26:28,848 --> 00:26:32,460
Yeah.
Wish me luck.

363
00:26:32,591 --> 00:26:33,722
He's the one
who's gonna need it.

364
00:26:37,900 --> 00:26:39,598
Be right back.

365
00:26:53,742 --> 00:26:56,745
If you take
Roosevelt island
as an example...

366
00:27:02,708 --> 00:27:04,971
Easy access
to Manhattan
for commuters.

367
00:27:05,101 --> 00:27:06,755
It's a gold mine.
Just wait.

368
00:27:06,886 --> 00:27:10,063
- Mr. Helmsley?
- Yes?

369
00:27:10,193 --> 00:27:13,501
I'm Leona Roberts.

370
00:27:13,632 --> 00:27:16,286
Would you care
to dance?

371
00:27:19,333 --> 00:27:21,683
I hear you're the best.

372
00:27:24,599 --> 00:27:26,340
Excuse me, gentlemen.

373
00:27:56,936 --> 00:27:58,502
You've taken lessons.

374
00:27:58,633 --> 00:28:02,506
No, I just follow.

375
00:28:02,637 --> 00:28:05,074
Something tells me,
miss Roberts,

376
00:28:05,205 --> 00:28:07,511
that you never
"just followed"

377
00:28:07,642 --> 00:28:09,731
in your life.

378
00:28:09,862 --> 00:28:13,430
That's because
I never found anybody
who could lead.

379
00:29:16,232 --> 00:29:18,887
Been a long time
since I've enjoyed
myself so much.

380
00:29:22,282 --> 00:29:24,937
Thank you,
miss Roberts.

381
00:29:25,067 --> 00:29:26,765
You're welcome,
Mr. Helmsley.

382
00:29:37,863 --> 00:29:39,865
So when are
you two kids
tying the knot?

383
00:29:39,995 --> 00:29:41,431
Oh, stop it.

384
00:29:43,738 --> 00:29:45,044
I'll tell you, baby,

385
00:29:45,174 --> 00:29:48,221
it is like meeting
Joe DiMaggio.

386
00:29:48,351 --> 00:29:49,875
Harry Helmsley?

387
00:29:50,005 --> 00:29:51,572
Yeah, I mean it.

388
00:29:51,702 --> 00:29:53,879
It's true!

389
00:29:54,009 --> 00:29:55,619
It's my dream.

390
00:29:55,750 --> 00:29:57,621
He's my hero.

391
00:29:57,752 --> 00:29:59,449
- Harry Helmsley?
- Harry Helmsley.

392
00:29:59,580 --> 00:30:01,756
Harry Helmsley owns
more of Manhattan

393
00:30:01,887 --> 00:30:04,672
than any single man
since the Indians
sold it.

394
00:30:04,803 --> 00:30:06,239
He is self-made,
he's clever,

395
00:30:06,369 --> 00:30:09,111
he's a great dancer.

396
00:30:09,242 --> 00:30:10,634
A perfect gentleman.

397
00:30:10,765 --> 00:30:13,724
Very attractive.

398
00:30:13,855 --> 00:30:16,945
- Too bad he's married.
- So was your last husband.

399
00:30:19,208 --> 00:30:21,254
Leo was never
married before.

400
00:30:21,384 --> 00:30:24,648
I'm not talking about Leo.
I'm talking about Joe.

401
00:30:24,779 --> 00:30:28,261
There was no Joe.

402
00:30:28,391 --> 00:30:31,264
Joe lubin, Leona,

403
00:30:31,394 --> 00:30:32,787
your second husband.

404
00:30:32,918 --> 00:30:36,660
I was married once
to Leo panzirer,

405
00:30:36,791 --> 00:30:37,879
the father of my son.

406
00:30:38,010 --> 00:30:40,708
Aha.

407
00:30:40,839 --> 00:30:42,579
So you're rewriting
your resume, huh?

408
00:30:42,710 --> 00:30:44,364
That's right.

409
00:30:44,494 --> 00:30:46,148
And if you keep
my secrets,

410
00:30:46,279 --> 00:30:48,063
I'll keep yours.

411
00:30:48,194 --> 00:30:51,023
I hope you'll both
be very happy.

412
00:30:51,153 --> 00:30:53,025
[ Both laugh ]

413
00:30:53,155 --> 00:30:55,027
You know something?

414
00:30:55,157 --> 00:30:58,682
I think we will.

415
00:30:58,813 --> 00:31:01,947
Man: <i>She's considered to be</i><i>
one of the leading real-estate</i><i>
brokers in the city,</i>

416
00:31:02,077 --> 00:31:04,775
<i>certainly a leader</i><i>
in converting rentals</i><i>
into co-ops</i>

417
00:31:04,906 --> 00:31:06,299
<i>and both</i><i>
"the New York times"</i>

418
00:31:06,429 --> 00:31:09,737
and "the post" have done
profiles on her.

419
00:31:09,868 --> 00:31:12,174
- [ Intercom buzzes ]
- Yes?

420
00:31:12,305 --> 00:31:14,307
Secretary: <i>Excuse me,</i><i>
Mr. Helmsley,</i>

421
00:31:14,437 --> 00:31:16,135
<i>but a miss Leona Roberts</i><i>
is here to see you.</i>

422
00:31:16,265 --> 00:31:17,788
<i>She doesn't have</i><i>
an appointment,</i>

423
00:31:17,919 --> 00:31:19,138
<i>but she insists</i><i>
on seeing you.</i>

424
00:31:19,268 --> 00:31:21,662
I'll bet she does.
Show her in.

425
00:31:21,792 --> 00:31:24,186
Thank you, Ron.
Good work.

426
00:31:24,317 --> 00:31:25,884
You're welcome, sir.

427
00:31:33,630 --> 00:31:36,024
Mr. Helmsley,
I presume.

428
00:31:36,155 --> 00:31:39,593
Miss Roberts.

429
00:31:40,594 --> 00:31:41,987
Woman: <i>This is all</i><i>
so confusing.</i>

430
00:31:42,117 --> 00:31:44,728
Woman #2: <i>I know.</i><i>
Okay, let me explain</i><i>
it to you, all right?</i>

431
00:31:44,859 --> 00:31:46,643
Under state law,

432
00:31:46,774 --> 00:31:50,125
if a landlord wants
to convert his buildings
from rentals to co-ops,

433
00:31:50,256 --> 00:31:53,259
he needs 35%
of his tenants
to agree.

434
00:31:53,389 --> 00:31:55,304
Now if he gets
the 35%,

435
00:31:55,435 --> 00:31:57,959
then those that
don't want to buy
can be evicted,

436
00:31:58,090 --> 00:31:59,918
their apartments
sold right out from
under them.

437
00:32:00,048 --> 00:32:01,876
But listen,
if they don't get
the percentage they need,

438
00:32:02,007 --> 00:32:05,880
then they can't go co-op,
and we get to keep
our apartments.

439
00:32:06,011 --> 00:32:07,751
- Woman: <i>That's not</i><i>
what they told me.</i>
- Who?

440
00:32:07,882 --> 00:32:09,666
Miss Roberts.
Her.

441
00:32:09,797 --> 00:32:13,235
<i>According to her,</i><i>
I could lose my apartment</i><i>
in 30 days.</i>

442
00:32:13,366 --> 00:32:15,281
All I said was
it was smart to buy
your apartment

443
00:32:15,411 --> 00:32:16,804
at the buyout
price now.

444
00:32:16,935 --> 00:32:18,937
She said I could
get evicted.

445
00:32:19,067 --> 00:32:20,851
It's true.
I'm trying
to protect you.

446
00:32:20,982 --> 00:32:23,463
I can't afford
to buy my apartment.

447
00:32:23,593 --> 00:32:25,508
The banks don't
give loans on co-ops.

448
00:32:25,639 --> 00:32:27,423
It'd take all my savings.

449
00:32:27,554 --> 00:32:28,424
I'm on a fixed income.

450
00:32:28,555 --> 00:32:31,210
If I lose my apartment,
where do I go?

451
00:32:31,340 --> 00:32:33,386
Wait, now everybody,
listen, okay?

452
00:32:33,516 --> 00:32:35,518
Co-op conversions
have been happening
all over the city

453
00:32:35,649 --> 00:32:38,173
and up until now,
tenants have run scared,

454
00:32:38,304 --> 00:32:39,827
signing over
their apartments
out of fear.

455
00:32:39,958 --> 00:32:41,481
But now we are
organizing.

456
00:32:41,611 --> 00:32:43,439
<i>We have a tenants'</i><i>
committee,</i>

457
00:32:43,570 --> 00:32:46,051
<i>and I assure you</i><i>
that if we stand</i><i>
together,</i>

458
00:32:46,181 --> 00:32:48,270
<i>we will win.</i>

459
00:32:48,401 --> 00:32:50,620
- <i>Okay?</i>
- <i>[ Applause and cheering ]</i>

460
00:32:53,580 --> 00:32:55,408
The tenants
voted US down.

461
00:32:55,538 --> 00:32:58,150
What's worse,
it happened in
two other buildings

462
00:32:58,280 --> 00:32:59,629
that Harry put me
in charge of.

463
00:32:59,760 --> 00:33:02,545
I never had a failure
with nederland.

464
00:33:02,676 --> 00:33:05,331
Now it's happened
three times in a row.

465
00:33:05,461 --> 00:33:08,377
Don't sweat it.
I know of an opening
if you need a job.

466
00:33:08,508 --> 00:33:11,467
Oh, honey, Harry would
never fire me now.

467
00:33:11,598 --> 00:33:14,818
It's much too late
for that.

468
00:33:14,949 --> 00:33:17,256
[ Doorbell chimes ]

469
00:33:31,009 --> 00:33:34,360
Well?
What do you think?

470
00:33:34,490 --> 00:33:36,710
Beautiful,

471
00:33:36,840 --> 00:33:38,668
just beautiful.

472
00:34:00,125 --> 00:34:02,605
I've never ever
felt this way before.

473
00:34:02,736 --> 00:34:04,825
You're the most beautiful
thing I've ever--

474
00:34:04,955 --> 00:34:06,348
shh.

475
00:34:06,479 --> 00:34:08,220
You deserve it, Harry.

476
00:34:08,350 --> 00:34:10,309
You're the king.

477
00:34:24,584 --> 00:34:26,890
Leona: <i>
Good morning, mama.</i>

478
00:34:27,021 --> 00:34:31,417
Look what
I got you.

479
00:34:31,547 --> 00:34:33,201
Your favorites.

480
00:34:34,420 --> 00:34:36,726
And...

481
00:34:39,425 --> 00:34:42,428
Cotton.
What do you think?

482
00:34:42,558 --> 00:34:44,343
Hmm?

483
00:34:47,433 --> 00:34:49,087
Perfect for spring.

484
00:34:52,699 --> 00:34:54,353
Did I tell you, mama?

485
00:34:57,399 --> 00:34:59,227
Jay is divorcing Myrna,

486
00:35:00,794 --> 00:35:02,839
gonna marry some girl
I don't even know.

487
00:35:02,970 --> 00:35:05,320
[ Chuckles ]

488
00:35:05,451 --> 00:35:08,149
But you'd be
proud of me.

489
00:35:14,155 --> 00:35:17,898
I am working for
Harry Helmsley.

490
00:35:18,028 --> 00:35:20,466
He owns almost
all of New York,

