Harry, you're not gonna
let this happen.

738
00:51:22,035 --> 00:51:24,211
Excuse US, please.

739
00:51:34,700 --> 00:51:37,529
You're the king, Harry.

740
00:51:37,659 --> 00:51:40,619
They can't treat you
like this.

741
00:51:40,749 --> 00:51:43,491
We practically
support this city
on the taxes you pay.

742
00:51:43,622 --> 00:51:47,321
Somebody out there
owes you a favor.

743
00:51:47,452 --> 00:51:50,411
Now you pick
up the phone,

744
00:51:50,542 --> 00:51:53,371
and you collect it.

745
00:52:03,424 --> 00:52:05,992
<i>[ Dialing phone ]</i>

746
00:52:06,123 --> 00:52:08,168
And I want
that lawyer fired.

747
00:52:16,611 --> 00:52:18,483
By the authority
vested in me

748
00:52:18,613 --> 00:52:20,398
by the state
of New York,

749
00:52:20,528 --> 00:52:23,009
I now pronounce you
man and wife.

750
00:52:23,140 --> 00:52:24,445
You may kiss the bride.

751
00:53:17,759 --> 00:53:20,458
- Look up, look up.
- Mm-hmm.

752
00:53:20,588 --> 00:53:22,851
Busy busy busy.
Watch your step.

753
00:53:27,595 --> 00:53:29,641
Well well well,
look what the cat
dragged in.

754
00:53:29,771 --> 00:53:32,078
- Mrs. Helmsley.
- Where have you been?

755
00:53:32,209 --> 00:53:33,688
Don't you ever
talk to your office?

756
00:53:33,819 --> 00:53:35,777
<i>I've been trying</i><i>
to reach you for days.</i>

757
00:53:35,908 --> 00:53:37,779
I was on a buying trip
with some other clients,
Mrs. Helmsley.

758
00:53:37,910 --> 00:53:39,564
It wasn't possible
to return your call.

759
00:53:39,694 --> 00:53:42,523
Oh, it wasn't possible.

760
00:53:42,654 --> 00:53:45,831
Well, you should have
made it possible.

761
00:53:45,961 --> 00:53:47,833
I pay you plenty,
buster.

762
00:53:47,963 --> 00:53:49,835
<i>And when I wanna</i><i>
talk to you,</i>

763
00:53:49,965 --> 00:53:52,577
I don't care where you are,
you get back to me pronto.

764
00:53:52,707 --> 00:53:55,449
I'm here now,
Mrs. Helmsley.
What's the problem?

765
00:53:55,580 --> 00:53:57,669
These chairs
are the problem.

766
00:53:57,799 --> 00:54:00,193
But those are the chairs
you had me bid on
at the auction.

767
00:54:00,324 --> 00:54:02,282
Well, the paper said
the whole lot were
second-rate,

768
00:54:02,413 --> 00:54:04,458
and anybody knowledgeable
would have passed on them.

769
00:54:04,589 --> 00:54:05,503
You told me
to bid on them.

770
00:54:05,633 --> 00:54:07,679
You should have
known better.

771
00:54:07,809 --> 00:54:10,551
And there is no way
that I am taking some
second-rate antiques.

772
00:54:10,682 --> 00:54:12,640
Just what do you
expect me to do
with them?

773
00:54:12,771 --> 00:54:15,513
- [ Laughs ]
- Paul: <i>Leona.</i>

774
00:54:17,689 --> 00:54:20,474
Well, I don't care
what you do with them,

775
00:54:20,605 --> 00:54:22,476
but they are not
staying here,

776
00:54:22,607 --> 00:54:24,217
and I am not
paying for them.

777
00:54:24,348 --> 00:54:26,654
You're quite right,
Mrs. Helmsley.

778
00:54:26,785 --> 00:54:28,613
There's only room
in this apartment

779
00:54:28,743 --> 00:54:29,831
for one second-rate
antique.

780
00:54:29,962 --> 00:54:31,572
You shall be hearing
from my lawyer.

781
00:54:34,532 --> 00:54:36,795
Oh, oh!
[ Laughing ]

782
00:54:36,925 --> 00:54:40,625
I'm glad you think
that's so funny.

783
00:54:40,755 --> 00:54:42,757
Oh, come on.
It was a hell
of a good line,

784
00:54:42,888 --> 00:54:44,672
and frankly,
you deserved it.

785
00:54:44,803 --> 00:54:46,457
If you weren't
so full of yourself

786
00:54:46,587 --> 00:54:47,675
you'd be breaking
up now too.

787
00:54:47,806 --> 00:54:49,677
There is no way
I'm gonna let some
little jerk

788
00:54:49,808 --> 00:54:51,505
who works for me
get away with that.

789
00:54:51,636 --> 00:54:53,464
He tried to make
a fool of me.

790
00:54:53,594 --> 00:54:55,509
Let it go, Leona.

791
00:54:55,640 --> 00:54:57,598
Why shouldn't
I be tough?

792
00:54:57,729 --> 00:55:00,035
Nobody ever
gave me anything
till Harry.

793
00:55:00,166 --> 00:55:02,647
<i>Why should I let</i><i>
anybody get away</i><i>
with anything?</i>

794
00:55:02,777 --> 00:55:04,562
You are always tough.

795
00:55:04,692 --> 00:55:05,998
That's one of the things
I like about you,

796
00:55:06,128 --> 00:55:08,653
- but you used to be fair.
- I'm still fair.

797
00:55:08,783 --> 00:55:11,569
No, you're mean now, Leona.
There's a difference.

798
00:55:11,699 --> 00:55:14,223
What kind of friend
are you?

799
